s of Gauguin's multilayered symbolism. The Symbolism of Paul Gauguin is lavishly illustrated with a major visual compendium of the artist's prodigious output. The highly readable narrative, based on a sophisticated understanding of Gauguin's oeuvre, offers a masterly interpretation of recurrent images and their interrelationships in the contemporaneous artistic and social context. Dorra discusses Gauguin's iconography and the artist's treatments of similar themes in various media, from prepatory drawings for paintings to related ceramics and wood carvings. He traces Gauguin's meanings in literary sources from classical mythology and the Bible to late ninetheenth-century literature. He also links the form and content of the artist's work to his unusual ancestry and upbringing. As the final scholarly work by an internationally recognized expert on nineteenth-century French symbolism, this book provides a profound new perspective on Gauguin and his work.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aArt. 4aEuropean. 7aART / European.2bisacsh1 aBrettell, Richard R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrettell, Richard R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDorra, Henri, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWeisberg, Gabriel P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeisberg, Gabriel P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024130540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093098840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520930988423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520930988/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of 